THE families of two cops are in mourning after they died in a collision between two heavy trucks and their police sedan. The two detective constables, who were colleagues and friends, travelled to work using the same vehicle. They were attached to the detective unit at Calcutta Police Station near Bushbuckridge, Mpumalanga. They had been on their way to Nelspruit. The horrific accident happened on the R40 road near Da Gama Dam between White River and Hazyview on Tuesday afternoon. It is alleged a truck hit their vehicle from behind, causing it to crash into another truck. Pat Ngomane, MEC for Community Safety, Security and Liaison, sent his heartfelt condolences to the affected families and colleagues of the two cops. Department spokesman Joseph Mabuza said the investigation to determine the cause of the accident was ongoing. The names of the two cops will only be released once its confirmed their families have been notified. The MEC called for hefty fines and jail sentences for reckless driving, saying it would contribute positively towards making roads safer and bring down incidences of reckless and negligent driving. Ngomane was responding to the sentencing of several motorists at Nelspruit Magistrates Court recently, mainly for speeding. A BMW X5 driver recorded the highest speed when he was bust driving 177 km/h in a 120 km/h zone. He was fined R4 000. Mpumalanga police spokesman Colonel Mtsholi Bhembe confirmed that police were investigating a case of culpable homicide.